  {
    "client_msg_id": "85094bd6-f6b3-4700-9047-3c34552c0963",
    "type": "message",
    "text": "I'm glad that my post started a discussion. For me, the biggest difference from sth like github would be that anyone could edit stuff that others have created initially. Take documentation / tests for example: When you are writing a piece of software, you understand how it works, so documentation is mostly for making it easier for others. But if you just started, not knowing whether your program is going to be used by others or even if's going to be useful, writing documentation would slow you down without providing an immediate benefit for you. So people don't write docs in the first place. On the other hand, a user discovering a piece of code who has just figured out how it works is more likely to write some docs to make understanding easier for others. If you find a program without tests that looks promising, but you don't know if it actually does what you need, you'd probably try some examples to test it. Wouldn't it be great if you could easily contribute these tests to the program? ",
    "user": "UAL7940NM",
