    "client_msg_id": "5fdfbec7-c1fe-45a1-9369-6bbdd63e28a9",
    "type": "message",
    "text": "<@UCGAK10LS> the difference I find important is that there's another concept of ownership. Github projects are owned by their maintainers and they need to accept your pull request. In a wiki system, changes are applied without anyone needing to approve beforehand. I think this would work great for comments / docs, and for code (which needs more stability), each edit could lead to a new version with references to other code snippets also targeting a specific versions. Users would manually update to new versions, probably assisted by ratings or whether an update breaks relevant tests. ",
